<div id="outline-container-org795a58d" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org795a58d">Linux Distributions, Package manager and repositories.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org795a58d">
<p>
Linux isn't a single OS. It is a large family tree of different
distributions all built on top of the linux kernel.  Each distribution
offers it's own package management, it's own set of applications, and
its own default desktop management system.  There are 3 main
distributions of which the other distributions build upon. Choosing a
distribution requires understanding the differences between them, the
use case you are planning on and the hardware you are using. ie if you
are building a mail server on a resource limited machine.  it should
inform your decision on distribution.
</p>

<p>
<a href="https://distrowatch.com/">Distro watch</a>
</p>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgcf59351" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgcf59351">Some Primary foundational distributions and some of their derivatives</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgcf59351">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Red Hat
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>RHEL</li>
<li>Cent OS</li>
<li>Fedora
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Fedora Jam (audio processing)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>

<li>Debian
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Ubuntu
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Mint</li>
</ul></li>
<li>kali</li>
<li>tails</li>
<li>Purism</li>
<li>raspbian</li>
<li>Mint (debian version)</li>
<li>antix</li>
<li>av linux (real time OS meant for audio processing)</li>
</ul></li>
<li>SUSE
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Open Suse</li>
</ul></li>

<li>Slackware</li>

<li>Android</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgb6a121c" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgb6a121c">Independent distrbutions for diy tinkerers</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgb6a121c">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Arch
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Manjaro</li>
<li>Steam OS</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Gentoo</li>
</ul>

<p>
Once we install a linux Distro how do we get software for it?
</p>

<ol class="org-ol">
<li>Download the src code, libraries and build scripts. Then compile
it yourself. This can sometimes be very challenging though a great learning
experience. Although may be smooth sailing if it's simple software.</li>

<li>Use the built in package manager for your distribution. This is almost like
the app store on ios or android.</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>


<div id="outline-container-org8210996" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org8210996">What is a package ?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org8210996">
<p>
A package is a set of pre-compiled binary files, installation
scripts, configuration files, dependency requirements and other
details about the software. When you as a programmer are building
software you have to realize you will not only need to write the code
but you will also need to package togther all the components for
distribution. Each platform may require a different package.
Packages are usually built for a specific distribution and possibly
for a specific release of that distribution. Packages are stored in
the distributions prefered file format.
</p>
</div>


<div id="outline-container-orgaa3c43b" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgaa3c43b">Package file formats</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-orgaa3c43b">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>.deb     debian</li>
<li>.rpm     CentOS/RHEL(red hat)</li>
<li>.tar.xz  Arch (these are compressed tar formats)</li>
<li>.tgz     Slackware</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org702d0ec" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org702d0ec">Software repositories</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org702d0ec">
<p>
A user can obtain a package from any method of file transfer, although
it is typical to use software repositories(repos) to obtain
packages. Repositories are file servers on the internet that store
packages. A repo may store 1 package or 1000. Most linux distributions
mantain their own repositories.  But anyone can host a repository.
These repositories usually hold and distribute packages based not only
on the flavor of linux but also for specific releases of that flavor. 
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org215110b" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org215110b">Dependencies</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org215110b">
<p>
Most software require certain supporting libraries to be installed on the system
for it run. Each package contains meta data that details the additionals software
and or software libraries that are needed. These additional software libraries are
called dependencies.  A single piece os software may require 100's of dependencies.
When installing, upgrading, removing packages, these dependencies may also need to
be tended to in the same way.
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgd92e6cd" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgd92e6cd">Package management software</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgd92e6cd">
<p>
Each distribution comes with their own package management software aka
package managers, and a built in list of software repositories whose
addresses are already built in to the system.  These package managers
make it very easy for a user to install, upgrade, or remove software
packages and dependencies on their systems.  Each package manager
comes with it's list of commands. Package managment software makes it
</p>

<ol class="org-ol">
<li>Easy to obtain stable and trusted releases of applications a user
may want to use.</li>
<li>Easy to manage dependencies</li>
<li>Follow conventions of a particuliar distro</li>
<li>Stay upto date on security and bug patches as
well as releases of feature enhancements</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org915ef38" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org915ef38">Common package mangers</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org915ef38">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org329443b" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org329443b">Debian based</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-org329443b">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Advanced Package Tool aka (apt)
Apt is actually a wrapper around a lower level
package tool called dpkg.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>


<div id="outline-container-orgbf8eac1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgbf8eac1">RHEl based -&gt; cent os/ Fedora</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-orgbf8eac1">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>DNF dandified yum Prior to the latest versions of RHEL version 8.
The package manager was yum, dnf is the replacment for
yum(yellow dog updater modified)</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org2e03dda" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org2e03dda">Arch</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-org2e03dda">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>pacman</li>
</ul>
<p>
packages are stored as compressed tarballs. These are more resource
friendly then other formats.
Arch also comes with a system to build packages as well as manage them.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>



<div id="outline-container-org4cd095f" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org4cd095f">Distribution History Use and Variance.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org4cd095f">
<p>
We need to know how Distributions are similirar and different from one
another. So we can choose the right distro for our function.  If we
want to build a Digital audio workstation we will chooe one
distributinon if we want to build a webserver we will choose another.
We can optimize the functionality of our systems by choosing the right
distribution.
</p>
</div>


